FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, BOVINE - UK (ENGLAND) (32)
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu 20 Sep 2007
Source: The Financial Times [edited]
<http://www.ft.com:80/cms/s/0/98fa6c0a-6706-11dc-a218-0000779fd2ac.html>

Animal health experts inspected a farm in the 2nd Surrey foot and mouth
disease [FMD] zone 3 times before discovering traces of the disease,
although livestock had been suffering from symptoms for more than 10 days,
it emerged on Wednesday [19 Sep 2007].
The finding at a farm known officially as IP5 indicates that FMD may have
been present in the animals prior to the discovery of an outbreak at
another farm near Egham, 10 miles (16 km) from the original outbreak in
early August [2007].
Controls were placed around the site of another suspected case of the
disease reported on Wednesday [19 Sep 2007] near Solihull in the West
Midlands. If tests prove positive it will be the most serious development
yet. However, there have been false alarms in various regions amid a state
of high alert.
The discovery that IP5 cattle and sheep, which were culled as a precaution
a few days ago, were found to have been showing clear symptoms of FMD was
"very concerning", said David Catlow, president of the British Veterinary
Association. Some of the animals bore lesions characteristic of the
disease, some of which had healed over, indicating they were probably more
than 10 days old.
The infected animals were part of a small herd of about 50 cattle and sheep.
Mr Catlow said: "This creates increased uncertainty. To find these lesions
that are 10 days old or more suggests there may be undisclosed disease, and
the potential for spreading it."
The government's report on how the disease spread will be published on
Friday [21 Sep 2007]. Debby Reynolds, chief veterinary officer, urged
farmers to check their animals at least twice a day for signs of illness,
rather than once as is standard.
The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs said the disease had
gone unnoticed at IP5 because lesions had healed over, making them
difficult to spot [see commentary].
Cattle and pigs are inspected for the disease, with pigs in the controlled
zone visited daily and cattle every other day. Sheep are given blood tests.
Peter Ainsworth, shadow environment secretary, said, "The fact that these
animals were infected at the time the government was giving the UK the all
clear is extremely alarming."
Angus Collingwood-Cameron, north east England director of the Country Land
and Business Association, said the export ban was causing difficulties for
farmers because sheep were mainly traded in September. "For some people
it's the only time of year when they get any income," he added.
[byline: Fiona Harvey, John O'Doherty, Chris Tighe]
--
