[2]
Date: Thu 20 Sep 2007
Source: The Guardian Unlimited [edited]
<http://www.guardian.co.uk/footandmouth/story/0,,2173440,00.html>

The foot and mouth virus could linger for months in autumn conditions, a
leading specialist said today [20 Sep 2007], in a warning that puts further
pressure on the government to order vaccination of livestock against the
disease.
Colin Fink, a virologist from Warwick University, said the virus could
survive for "a very long time in cool conditions." He gave the warning
ahead of the release of a government report on how the disease spread from
Pirbright to Egham.
Speaking to BBC Radio's Farming Today, Dr Fink said: "The longer they wait
and vacillate about vaccination, the more this is going to become
entrenched. We have a major problem because without the sunshine to destroy
the virus in the field, we're going to have the virus around for a long time."
The Soil Association told Guardian Unlimited that the government appears to
be "on the brink" of launching a vaccination programme. "If there's one
more case outside the protection zone, I expect they will vaccinate," said
Phil Stocker, the association's head of food and farming. "The longer this
goes on, the stronger the evidence gets for vaccination."
The government's Institute for Animal Health at Pirbright, the suspected
source of the July [2007] leak of the virus, has said it can now test for
foot and mouth in an hour using a technique "analogous to the home
pregnancy test."
Mr Stocker said this added to the argument for vaccination rather than
precautionary culls. "The unnecessary slaughter of healthy cattle is
abhorrent. They are on the brink of changing policy, but they don't seem to
be able to make a decision." On Tuesday [18 Sep 2007], the chief vet, Debby
Reynolds, repeated that vaccination was being "kept under constant review."
The government is believed to be reluctant to vaccinate because of EU
export rules and pressure from farmers. Meat from countries where there has
been foot and mouth vaccination is banned for export for 6 months. But
culling only invokes a 3 month ban.
Mr Stocker said: "The farming industry is not as hostile as it was to
vaccination, but I would not be surprised if there are elements lobbying
against it. If the government sticks to the science [as it has pledged to
do], they will vaccinate now and not bow to pressure from industry."
[byline: Matthew Weaver]
