[3]
Date: Thu 20 Sep 2007
Source: Solihull Metropolitan Borough Council website [edited]
<http://www.solihull.gov.uk/section.asp?catid=200183&docid=2394>

A Temporary Control Zone has been put around one premise in the Catherine
de Barnes area of Solihull. This is a precautionary measure. An assessment
of clinical symptoms by Animal Health veterinary staff has been carried
out, and laboratory test results are awaited. At this stage disease has not
been confirmed. We will be working closely with DEFRA (UK Department for
Environment, Food, and Rural Affairs) and up to date information will be on
our website.
The following restrictions are now in place:
- no animals are to be moved within, into, or out of the Control Zone
- at this stage all footpaths within Solihull remain open. We would however
ask the public to sympathise with the concerns of farmers, and avoid using
footpaths within the Control Zone until further notice.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[In view of the possibility that FMD had gone unnoticed at IP5 in spite of
several clinical inspections, the possible application of rapid pen-side
test for FMD deserves to be seriously considered.
For background see ProMED-mail post 20060924.2730, item [3], which includes
the abstract of the following reference: NP Ferris, DP King, SM Reid, AE
Shaw, GH Hutchings. Comparisons of original laboratory results and
retrospective analysis by real-time reverse transcriptase-PCR of
virological samples collected from confirmed cases of foot-and-mouth
disease in the UK in 2001. Vet Rec 2006; 159: 373-8.
Results of yesterday's [19 Sep 2007] suspected case in Solihull will be
posted as soon as becoming available. - Mod.AS]
